center| 2\n|align=center| 59\n| bgcolor=\"#C0C0C0\"|{{sortname|Deron|Washington}}<sup>#</sup>\n| SF\n| {{flagu|United States}}\n| [[Detroit Pistons]]\n| [[Virginia Tech Hokies men's basketball|Virginia Tech]] <small>([[Senior (education)|Sr.]])</small>\n|-\n|align=center| 2\n|align=center| 60\n| {{sortname|Semih|Erden}}\n| C\n| {{TUR}}\n| [[Boston Celtics]]\n| [[Fenerbah\u00e7e Men's Basketball|Fenerbah\u00e7e \u00dclker]] <small>([[Turkish Basketball League|Turkey]])</small>\n|}\n{{reflist|group=n}}\n{{Cnote|a|The franchise relocated to become the [[Oklahoma City Thunder]] in July 2008.<ref name=\"thunder\"/>}}\n{{Cnote|b|Anthony Randolph was born in [[West Germany]] to American parents and was raised in the United States. He became a naturalized citizen of Slovenia in 2017 and he has represented [[Slovenia national basketball team|Slovenia]] internationally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.sfgate.com/2009-01-28/sports/17197570_1_randolph-s-parents-school-coach-arkansas|title=Warriors' Randolph trying to fit in|first=Janny|last=Hu|date=January 28, 2009|work=San Francisco Chronicle|accessdate=October 17, 2010}}</ref> <ref>{{cite news|title=Randolph joins Slovenia for EuroBasket|url=http://www.eurohoops.net/en/national-teams/469359/randolph-joins-slovenia-eurobasket/|accessdate=June 23, 2017|work=Eurohoops.net|date=June 23, 2017}}</ref>}}\n{{Cnote|c|Roy Hibbert was born in the United States to a [[Jamaica]]n father and a [[Trinidad and Tobago|Trinidadian]] mother. He had represented the United States internationally at youth level in 2007.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/story/2007/12/21/ST2007122102522.html|title=Fast Friends, Big Rivals|first=Camille|last=Powell|date=December 22, 2007|work=The Washington Post|publisher=The Washington Post|accessdate=August 15, 2011}}</ref> Since 2010, he has represented [[Jamaica national basketball team|Jamaica]] internationally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsjamaica.com/read_article.php?id=18463|title=Jamaica's Hibbert working hard to reach the top|first=Gordon|last=Williams|date=January 19, 2011|work=Sports Jamaica|publisher=Jamaica Gleaner|accessdate=August 15, 2011}}</ref>}}\n{{Cnote|d|Kosta Koufos was born and raised in the United States to Greek parents. He has represented [[Greece national basketball team|Greece]] internationally.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fibaeurope.com/container_frontpage.coid_TwXRRK,lH3IVPkIJJiBau2.articleMode_on.html|title=Greek Star Koufos Keeps Feet On The Ground|first=Daniel|last=Aubrey|date=August 9, 2007|work=FIBA Europe|publisher=FIBA|accessdate=August 15, 2011}}</ref>}}\n{{Cnote|e|Serge Ibaka, who was born in [[Republic of the Congo|Congo]], became a naturalized citizen of Spain in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://espn.go.com/nba/story/_/id/6804350/serge-ibaka-help-adopted-spain-defend-euros-title|title=Serge Ibaka to boost talented Spain|date=July 26, 2011|work=ESPN.com|accessdate=August 15, 2011}}</ref> He has represented [[Spain national basketball team|Spain]] internationally since 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fibaeurope.com/coid_0fRrDVPpIgktm,Rny3wba3.articleMode_on.html|title=Pau Show as Spain Down France|date=August 9, 2011|work=FIBA Europe|publisher=FIBA|accessdate=August 15, 2011}}</ref>}}\n{{Cnote|f|Dont\u00e9 Greene was born in [[West Germany]] to American parents. He has represented the United States internationally at youth level.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1106915/index.htm|title=Greener Pastures|date=January 22, 2007|first=Franz|last=Lidz|work=Sports Illustrated|publisher=Time Warner Company|accessdate=October 17, 2010}}</ref>}}\n{{Cnote|g|James Gist was born in Turkey to American parents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://spor.milliyet.com.tr/adanali-fener-e-dogru/spor/spordetay/28.04.2011/1383409/default.htm |title=Adanal\u0131 Fener\u2019e do\u011fru |language=Turkish |trans-title=Fener to Adana |date=April 28, 2011 |work=Milliyet.com.tr |publisher=Demir\u00f6ren-Karacan |accessdate=September 19, 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728065415/http://spor.milliyet.com.tr/adanali-fener-e-dogru/spor/spordetay/28.04.2011/1383409/default.htm |archivedate=July 28, 2011 }}</ref>}}\n\n==Notable undrafted players==\nThese players were not selected in the 2008 NBA Draft but have played in the NBA.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable sortable\"\n|-\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Player\n! style=\"width:1%;\"| Position\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| Nationality\n! style=\"width:12%;\"| School/club team\n|-\n|{{sortname|Gary|Forbes}}\n|SF\n|{{PAN}}\n|[[UMass Minutemen basketball|UMass]] (Sr.)\n|-\n|{{sortname|Sundiata|Gaines}}\n|PG\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|[[Georgia Bulldogs men's basketball|Georgia]] (Sr.)\n|-\n|{{sortname|Mickell|Gladness}}\n|C\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|[[Alabama A&M Bulldogs basketball|Alabama A&M]] (Sr.)\n|-\n|{{sortname|Steven|Hill|Steven Hill (basketball)}}\n|PF\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|[[Arkansas Razorbacks men's basketball|Arkansas]] (Sr.)\n|-\n|{{sortname|Othello|Hunter}}\n|F\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|[[Ohio State Buckeyes men's basketball|Ohio State]] (Sr.)\n|-\n|{{sortname|Othyus|Jeffers}}\n|SG\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|[[Robert Morris University (Illinois)#Athletics|Robert Morris (IL)]] (Sr.)\n|-\n|{{sortname|Rob|Kurz}}\n|SF\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|[[Notre Dame Fighting Irish men's basketball|Notre Dame]] (Sr.)\n|-\n|{{sortname|Salah|Mejri}}\n|C\n|{{TUN}}\n|[[\u00c9toile Sportive du Sahel (basketball)|\u00c9toile Sportive du Sahel]] ([[Tunisian Division I Basketball League|Tunisia]])\n|-\n|{{sortname|Gal|Mekel}}\n|PG\n|{{ISR}}\n|[[Wichita State Shockers men's basketball|Wichita State]] (So.)\n|-\n|{{sortname|Anthony|Morrow}}\n|SG\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|[[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets men's basketball|Georgia Tech]] (Sr.)\n|-\n|{{sortname|Timofey|Mozgov}}\n|C\n|{{flagu|Russia}}\n|[[Khimki Moscow Region|Khimki Moscow]] ([[Russian Professional Basketball League|Russia]])\n|-\n|{{sortname|DeMarcus|Nelson}}\n|PG\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|[[Duke Blue Devils men's basketball|Duke]] (Sr.)\n|-\n|{{sortname|Brian|Roberts|dab = basketball}}\n|PG\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|[[Dayton Flyers men's basketball|Dayton]] (Sr.)\n|-\n|{{sortname|Damjan|Rude\u017e}}\n|F\n|{{CRO}}\n|[[KK Split]] (Croatia)\n|-\n|{{sortname|Greg|Stiemsma}}\n|C\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|[[Wisconsin Badgers men's basketball|Wisconsin]] (Sr.)\n|-\n|{{sortname|Reggie|Williams|Reggie Williams (basketball, born 1986)}}\n|SF\n|{{flagu|United States}}\n|[[VMI Keydets basketball|VMI]] (Sr.)\n|}\n\n==Eligibility==\n{{main|Eligibility for the NBA Draft}}\n\n==Draft Lottery==\n{{further|NBA Draft Lottery}}\nThe first 14 picks in the draft belonged to teams that had missed the [[2008 NBA Playoffs|playoffs]]; the order was determined through a lottery. The lottery determined the three teams that would obtain the first three picks on the draft. The remaining first-round picks and the second-round picks were assigned to teams in reverse order of their win-loss record in the [[2007\u201308 NBA season|previous season]]. As it is commonplace in the event of identical win-loss records, the NBA performed a random drawing to break the ties on April 18, 2008.<ref name=\"draftorder\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/clippers/news/08lottery_ties_080418.html|title=Ties Broken for NBA Draft 2008 Order of Selection|date=April 18, 2008|work=NBA.com|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc|accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe lottery was held on May 20, 2008, in [[Secaucus, New Jersey]].<ref name=\"draftorder\"/>  The [[Chicago Bulls]], who had the ninth-worst record, won the lottery with just a 1.7% chance to win. The [[Miami Heat]] and [[Minnesota Timberwolves]], with the worst and third-worst records, respectively, won the second and third picks.\n\nBelow were the chances for each team to get specific picks in the 2008 draft lottery, rounded to three decimal places:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/nba_news/draft_lottery_results_080520.html|title=Results of the 2008 NBA Draft Lottery|date=May 20, 2008|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc|work=NBA.com|accessdate=April 18, 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100913110915/http://www.nba.com/nba_news/draft_lottery_results_080520.html|archive-date=September 13, 2010|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nba.com/pacers/news/lottery_odds_2008.html|title=2008 NBA Draft Lottery odds|date=May 20, 2008|publisher=Turner Sports Interactive, Inc|work=NBA.com|accessdate=April 18, 2011}}</ref>\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n| style=\"background-color:#FFFF99; border:1px solid #aaaaaa; width:2em\"| ^\n|Denotes the actual lottery results\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" align=\"left\" | Team || rowspan=\"2\" | [[2007\u201308 NBA season|2007\u201308<br> record]] || rowspan=\"2\" |Lottery<br> chances || colspan=\"14\" | Pick\n|-\n! 1st || 2nd || 3rd || 4th || 5th || 6th || 7th || 8th || 9th || 10th || 11th || 12th || 13th || 14th\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[Miami Heat]] || 15\u201367 || 250\n| .250 || style=\"background-color:#FFFF99\"|.215^ || .177 || .358 ||align=\"center\"|\u2014||align=\"center\"|\u2014||align=\"center\"|\u2014||align=\"center\"|\u2014||align=\"center\"|\u2014||align=\"center\"|\u2014||align=\"center\"|\u2014||align=\"center\"|\u2014||align=\"center\"|\u2014||align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[Seattle SuperSonics]] || 20\u201362 || 199\n| .199 || .188 || .171 || style=\"background-color:#FFFF99\"|.319^ || .124 ||align=\"center\"|\u2014||align=\"center\"|\u2014||align=\"center\"|\u2014||align=\"center\"|\u2014||align=\"center\"|\u2014||align=\"center\"|\u2014||align=\"center\"|\u2014||align=\"center\"|\u2014||align=\"center\"|\u2014\n|-\n| align=\"left\" | [[Minnesota Timberwolves]] || 22\u201360 || 138\n| .138 || .142 || style=\"background-color:#FFFF99\"|.145^ || .238 || .290 || .045 ||align=\"center\"|\u2